Using the rule $(x, y) \to (kx, ky)$:
\[
 B(2, 3) \to B'(-2 \cdot 2, -2 \cdot 3) = B'(-4, -6)
\]

With a negative scale factor, the image is on the opposite side of 
the center (origin) from the original point, and twice as far away.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.5]
 % Grid
 (-6,-7) grid (4,5);
 (-6,0) – (4.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
 (0,-7) – (0,5.5) node[above] {$y$};

 % Original point
 ll[AtlasTeal] (2,3) circle (5pt);
 at (2,3) {$B(2, 3)$};

 % Image point
 ll[AtlasWarm] (-4,-6) circle (5pt);
 at (-4,-6) {$B'(-4, -6)$};

 % Origin
 ll[AtlasSage] (0,0) circle (4pt);
 at (0.2,0) {$O$};

 % Line through origin
 (-4,-6) – (2,3);
tikzpicture
center

Apply $(x, y) \to (2x, 2y)$:
$$
 P(1, 2) &\to P'(2, 4) \\
 Q(4, 2) &\to Q'(8, 4) \\
 R(2, 5) &\to R'(4, 10)
$$

